  "prompt": "What's the difference between I++ and ++I in C?",
  "response": "In C, `i++` and `++i` are both increment operators, but they differ in their behavior:\n\n1. `i++` (Post-increment):\n```c\nint i = 5;\nint j = i++;  // j will be 5, i becomes 6\n```\n- Returns the original value BEFORE incrementing\n- The increment happens AFTER the value is used\n- Creates a temporary copy of the original value\n\n2. `++i` (Pre-increment):\n```c\nint i = 5;\nint j = ++i;  // j will be 6, i becomes 6\n```\n- Increments the value BEFORE returning it\n- Returns the incremented value\n- More efficient as it doesn't create a temporary copy\n\nExample to illustrate the difference:\n```c\nint i = 5;\nprintf(\"%d %d\", i++, ++i);  \n// This might print: 5 7 (behavior can be unpredictable)\n```\n\nPerformance:\n- `++i` is slightly more efficient, especially with complex types\n- For simple integers, modern compilers optimize both to similar machine code\n\nBest practice:\n- Use `++i` when you want the incremented value\n- Use `i++` when you want the original value before incrementing\n\nIn most simple cases, they work identically for integers.",
